properties.name: Advice
properties.location: the Ovens Rocky point to Wangaratta
properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for the Ovens Rocky point to Wangaratta.

MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE IN NORTH EAST VICTORIA WITH THE CHANCE OF ISOLATED HIGHER LEVELS FROM SATURDAY   

A cold front will reach western Victoria later on Thursday, then cross the State on Friday, followed by a second, stronger front overnight Friday into Saturday. These fronts will bring showers, with the highest rainfall totals expected to be observed during Saturday.   

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are already relatively wet. River and stream levels are already elevated due to rainfall over the last week, with minor flooding having only recently subsided in some catchments.   

Rainfall is expected to be higher during the afternoon and evening periods on Thursday and Friday, with daily totals of up to 10 mm on Thursday and 20 mm on Friday possible.   

Rainfall will be highest during Saturday with daily rainfall totals of around 20 - 40 mm possible with higher isolated totals possible in elevated areas.   

Renewed river level rises and minor flooding are possible from Saturday and into Sunday. Higher levels, including isolated moderate flooding, are possible in some credible higher alternative rainfall scenarios.   

Catchments likely to be affected include: 
Upper Murray and Mitta Mitta Rivers 
Kiewa River (minor warning current) 
Ovens and King Rivers

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 07/07/2023 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham.

  • Floodwaters from the Murray River tributaries upstream of Barham combined with floodwaters from the local tributaries have caused minor flooding along the Murray River at Barham.
  • The Murray River at Barham is currently at 5.58 metres and rising slowly, above the minor flood level (5.50 metres)
  • The Murray River at Barham may reach around 5.70 metres near the end of the week, with minor flooding.
  • The peak forecast at Barham will be provided once upstream peaks have been observed.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area:

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the King River at Docker Rd Bridge .

MINOR FLOODING MAY DEVELOP AT DOCKER ROAD BRIDGE EARLY FRIDAY MORNING

River levels are elevated along the King River at Docker Rd Bridge due to recent rainfall. With a relatively wet catchment and rainfall forecast of up to 10 mm overnight Thursday into Friday, minor flooding may develop along the King River at Docker Rd Bridge from early Friday morning.

Showers are forecast for the next few days, with more significant rainfall possible over the weekend in conjunction with a cold front. River levels are likely to remain elevated for the next few days with further rises possible with forecast rainfall.

King River:
Minor flooding may occur along the King River.

The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is currently at 3.28 metres and steady, below the minor flood level (3.70m). The King River at Docker Rd Bridge may reach the minor flood level (3.70m) early Friday morning.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Cape Conran, Marlo.

  • Due to a whale carcass that remains on the beach, there could be an increase in shark activity reported at Point Ricardo.
  • A whale carcass can attract sharks to the area and mean they are closer to the shore than normal.
  • While it is not uncommon for sharks to be present off the Victorian coast, you should exercise additional caution in the area.
  • This is an update, replacing the Advice issued on 23 June.
Avoid the area. Stay informed and do not enter the water at closed beaches.
What you should do:

  • If you see sharks, report the sighting by calling Triple Zero (000) or notify lifesavers immediately if you are at a patrolled beach.
Staying safe at nearby beaches:
  • Always swim, dive or surf with a friend.
  • Swim between the red and yellow flags on patrolled beaches.
  • Don't swim in places where human or animal waste enters the water.
  • Keep away from large schools of fish, seals or other wildlife as these can attract sharks.
Impacts in your area:
  • Victorian Fisheries Authority is assisting wildlife officers and park rangers with the management of the whale carcass.
This message was issued by Victorian Fisheries Authority.

The next update is expected by 07/07/2023 05:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.   
Accessibility:

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

Minor flooding is expected to continue along the Kiewa River at Bandiana.

In the 24 hours to 1:00 pm Thursday, no significant rainfall has been recorded across the Kiewa River catchment.

Showers are forecast for the next few days, with more significant rainfall possible over the weekend in conjunction with a cold front. River levels are likely to remain elevated for the next few days, with further river level rises possible with forecast rainfall.

Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge:
Minor flooding is occurring along the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

The Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) is currently at 3.14 metres and steady, below the minor flood level (3.30 m). A below minor peak is likely in the Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) Thursday afternoon. The river level is likely to remain below the minor flood level (3.30 m) for the remainder of Thursday into Friday.
Further rises and minor flooding possible (3.30 m) from Saturday, with forecast rainfall.

The Kiewa River at Bandiana peaked at 2.94 metres overnight Wednesday with minor flooding, and is currently at 2.92 metres and steady. The Kiewa River at Bandiana is expected to remain above the minor flood level (2.80 m) for the remainder of Thursday into Friday.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal.

MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE AT COROWA   

Floodwaters from the Murray River tributaries combined with floodwaters from the local tributaries may cause minor flooding along the Murray River at Corowa. 

Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal: 
Minor flooding may occur along the Murray River at Corowa.   
The Murray River at Corowa is currently at 4.42 metres and rising slowly. The Murray River at Corowa may reach the minor flood level (4.60 m) from Friday into the weekend.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
  • Parks, hiking tracks and campgrounds are closed due to flooding. To find out more go to www.parkweb.vic.gov.au/safety/flood-affected-parks.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 07/07/2023 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Next Update: Friday 07 July 2023, 02:00 pm

More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/29683/moreinfo

This Flood Watch is being issued for the Kiewa River to Mongans Bridge.

MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE IN NORTH EAST VICTORIA WITH THE CHANCE OF ISOLATED HIGHER LEVELS FROM SATURDAY    

A cold front will reach western Victoria later on Thursday, then cross the State on Friday, followed by a second, stronger front overnight Friday into Saturday. These fronts will bring showers, with the highest rainfall totals expected to be observed during Saturday.    

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are already relatively wet. River and stream levels are already elevated due to rainfall over the last week, with minor flooding having only recently subsided in some catchments.    

Rainfall is expected to be higher during the afternoon and evening periods on Thursday and Friday, with daily totals of up to 10 mm on Thursday and 20 mm on Friday possible.    

Rainfall will be highest during Saturday with daily rainfall totals of around 20 - 40 mm possible with higher isolated totals possible in elevated areas.    

Renewed river level rises and minor flooding are possible from Saturday and into Sunday. Higher levels, including isolated moderate flooding, are possible in some credible higher alternative rainfall scenarios.    

Catchments likely to be affected include: 
Upper Murray and Mitta Mitta Rivers 
Kiewa River (minor warning current) 
Ovens and King Rivers 



Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE IN NORTH EAST VICTORIA WITH THE CHANCE OF ISOLATED HIGHER LEVELS FROM SATURDAY

A cold front will reach western Victoria later on Thursday, then cross the State on Friday, followed by a second, stronger front overnight Friday into Saturday. These fronts will bring showers, with the highest rainfall totals expected to be observed during Saturday.

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are already relatively wet. River and stream levels are already elevated due to rainfall over the last week, with minor flooding having only recently subsided in some catchments.

Rainfall is expected to be higher during the afternoon and evening periods on Thursday and Friday, with daily totals of up to 10 mm on Thursday and 20 mm on Friday possible.

Rainfall will be highest during Saturday with daily rainfall totals of around 20 - 40 mm possible with higher isolated totals possible in elevated areas.

Renewed river level rises and minor flooding are possible from Saturday and into Sunday. Higher levels, including isolated moderate flooding, are possible in some credible higher alternative rainfall scenarios.

Catchments likely to be affected include:
  • Upper Murray and Mitta Mitta Rivers
  • Kiewa River (minor warning current)
  • Ovens and King Rivers

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 07/07/2023 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
